    "narrative": "Our lineup for today, 2026-04-21, centers on attacking favorable matchups against high-xERA arms, headlined by the slate\u2019s premier play, **Corbin Carroll** (87.14). Facing Sean Burke, **Corbin Carroll** benefits from a distinct advantage on the basepaths; his ability to capitalize on a slow delivery earns him a +4% boost to his efficiency, making him an elite start. Similarly, **James Wood** (78.42) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) are set to anchor our outfield against vulnerable pitching. **James Wood** leverages a prime leadoff spot against the 6.36 xERA of Reynaldo L\u00f3pez, while **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a significant park factor boost and the weak profile of Randy V\u00e1squez. Both **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.01), **Trevor Story** (72.05), and **Brice Turang** (71.53) round out a strong core of hitters in the 70+ range, each benefiting from advantageous platoon splits or weak opposing starters like Luis Gil and Keider Montero.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Alex Freeland** (49.73), who fell just shy of cracking the lineup for **Jose Caballero**. While **Alex Freeland** presented a decent profile, the optimizer favored **Jose Caballero**'s superior platoon edge against the lefty Connelly Early, despite the latter's tough xERA profile. Caution is warranted elsewhere: **Dalton Rushing** (51.38) carries a 35% rain risk in his matchup against Landen Roupp, and while his base profile is viable, we are closely monitoring the weather before locking him in. Meanwhile, **Seiya Suzuki** (51.64) remains a marginal play as he faces Jes\u00fas Luzardo; the combination of a stingy opposing arm and the risk posed by an elite hold pitcher on the basepaths limits his ceiling for today\u2019s stolen base targets. Owners should keep a close watch on official lineups for **Luis Campusano** and **Kyle Karros**, as any shift down the order could further dampen their already marginal scoring projections.",
